{{DISPLAYTITLE:The Schimmelplatz}}
{{Background|file=TheSchimmelplatz.webp}}
{{Class Deadzone}}

'''The Schimmelplatz''', sometimes referred to as “'''Der Schimmelplatz'''”, is an anomalous level found within The Backrooms. The Schimmelplatz is currently under investigation, as its properties are highly mysterious.

==<span style="color:white;">Description</span>==

'''The Schimmelplatz''' takes the appearance of an underground highway, expanding for an unfathomable length. The Schimmelplatz is made incredibly dangerous by its mold infestation, appearing across the dingy, bleak walls throughout the tunnel. The roads within the tunnel appear to be indestructible, resisting all attempts to break through and investigate deeper. The mold also appears to share this property of extreme durability, displaying enhanced resistance to many forms of weaponry, only faltering under the most extreme conditions. 

The Schimmelplatz was discovered in the year 1998 by an anonymous German wanderer, who dubbed it with the official designation of “Level 234”. This designation was later dropped, likely to insinuate the level’s environmental hazards to unknowing wanderers. When the designation was dropped, the level took up the moniker of “The Schimmelplatz" (sometimes referred to as “Der Schimmelplatz”) to honor the discovery team’s nickname for the level, roughly translating to “The Mold Place” in German. This moniker has faced major criticism from major organizations, individuals, and research teams within The Backrooms, primarily due to the choice of the German language as the official designation.  {{Blurimage|file=Schimmelplatz2.webp|align=Center|caption=A more dilapidated region of this level. Photographer’s status is currently unknown.}}

Throughout the level, diverse landscapes and buildings wait longingly for a wanderer’s attention. Some buildings generate at set locations, prompting them to spawn in said area every time the wanderer reaches that portion of the level. Other buildings procedurally generate across the level, defying our current understanding of geometry and physics. Among the level’s highly diverse range of buildings, landscapes, and cityscapes, one factor remains constant: There is no (known) above ground. Any and all features of this level are stored within the depths of the underground, and it is currently unknown whether an above-ground exists. A theory popularized by German Non-Euclidean physicist Klara Andersen states that The Schimmelplatz was once a sprawling, suburban level that was engulfed by the mold inhabiting the caverns stowed below the original level. This theory has been met with relative positivity from the general public, however, the overarching Backrooms scientific community has scrutinized and objected to the concept on several occasions. The following statement was made against this theory by an anonymous Backrooms physicist:

{{Quote|Mold infestations do not just... materialize underground. Her claims are baseless, considering that Klara is unable to provide substantial evidence as to back up this theory.}}

Throughout the level’s tunnels and catacombs, many “town-like” structures can be found. These buildings may serve as counterparts to shops, banks, restaurants, pubs, homesteads, and, on rare occasions, nightclubs. Of these structures, nightclubs may have the most significant impact on the wanderer’s visit. Nightclubs contain many beverages akin to those in reality, providing the wanderer a sense of normalcy, even within a hazardous level such as The Schimmelplatz. Despite the inviting nature of these abodes, it is imperative that one does not stop for an extended duration of time. Stopping for too long could cause one to grow tired, culminating in their potential demise from the advancing mold wall.   

The rancid smell of rotting food, mold, and other various sources wafts throughout the level at a constant rate. The source of this stench has not been, and likely cannot be located. Interestingly, the smell has a property that prevents wanderers from becoming noseblind to it. No matter the length of the wanderer’s stay, they will not overcome the stench. The smell can grow so extreme at times that chemical burns develop on the nose, or within the nasal passages. A large portion of interviewed wanderers report the stench remaining within their nasal passages after escaping the level, however, there is little scientific basis for this phenomenon, and it is likely a symptom of Post Traumatic Stress Disorder. Alike the stench, inhalation of mold can cause wanderers to slowly lose respiratory function. This happens with non-anomalous mold due to the mold residue building up within the lungs, however, the mold found within The Schimmelplatz takes a far slower, more agonizing approach. If the wanderer has no protection against the mold, the mold will begin to develop within the trachea. After 24-36 hours, the mold will begin to savagely eat away at the skin lining the trachea, causing unbearable pain. The affliction generally concludes with a "bursting" of the neck, immediately decapitating the infected person.

{{Blurimage|file=Schimmelplatz3.webp|align=center|caption=A corridor found within the early regions of the level. Photographer was part of an experienced expeditionary group.}}

The mold employs many “traps” to immobilize, incapacitate, and kill the wanderer. One of such traps takes the appearance of a large spider web, however it is held together using nearly transparent mold. The web has an incredibly intricate structure, using the most minute of techniques to ensure the wanderer’s immobility. These webs often go unnoticed by the wanderer, as the webs appear later in the level, only once the wanderer is less alert due to sleepiness. The webs are nearly indestructible, requiring extreme force akin to that of several explosions or a wrecking ball to be dismantled. These webs can be avoided by crawling beneath them, as the webs do not generally extend to the floor. If the web continues to extend to the ground, the most favorable course of action is to search for an alternative route, as several tunnels usually appear around the main pathway. 

Along with the web traps, the level also employs pitfall traps. Pitfalls generally take the appearance of vast, gaping holes in the ground. These pitfalls are easily noticed; however, they require extreme precision to be maneuvered. The bottoms of these pitfalls are the mold’s breeding grounds, being the most common location for spore production. Some adult specimens may stay at the bottom of the pitfalls, forming into a biologically structured spike, impaling any wanderer who may fall. 

Throughout the wanderer’s visit on the level, they will be in constant pursuit by an incredibly slow-moving wall of mold, advancing as the wanderer continues walking. There are no known ways to stop, destroy, or prevent the oncoming movement of this wall. The wall often swallows up slumbersome wanderers, sealing their partially unknown, yet almost certainly grisly fate. The coloration of the mold is useless in determining the species, as the entire wall is shaded with a puke green tint. Due to the existence of this mold wall, it is not recommended to rest, lay down, or sleep on the level.

==<span style="color:white;">Entities</span>==

The level does not contain entities under their usual definition; however, the mold of the level could be considered an entity due to its biological nature. The Schimmelplatz currently hosts three known species of mold and grime. 

One thing remains constant among every species of mold: Their resilience. Every species of mold, even the least hearty of them is capable of surviving conditions on par with that of extremophile organisms (such as Archaebacteria) in [[The Frontrooms]]. The mold shows resistance to temperatures as high as 588 Kelvins and, very interestingly, as low as 0 Kelvin. This is incredibly interesting because, at a temperature that low, particles at the atomic level cease all motion, generating absolutely no heat. The mold at this temperature appears to begin rapidly producing a previously undocumented chemical, slowing down their body function and essentially freezing their entire structure. The organisms are remarkably swift to begin awakening after temperature increases, regaining cognitive and physical function within milliseconds.

{{Quote|Der Schimmel verschlingt ohne Rücksicht auf das Leben. (The mold devours with no regard for life).|Famous German wanderer Hugo “Stahlmann” Klein.}}

===<span style="color:white;">White Mold</span>===

White Mold is by far the most common strain of mold found throughout the level. White Mold is the gold standard for species on the level, slaughtering the most wanderers out of the three. White Mold can grow in nearly every crevice found within the level, spreading their influence tenfold compared to the surrounding species. White Mold displays similar physical characteristics to Black Mold and Blood Mold, but it is important to understand that they are not the same. White Mold is best identified by its white coloration, which generally sets it apart from the other species. White Mold can also be identified by its tendency to form into needle-like structures.

White Mold appears to take a more violent approach to attacking wanderers, choosing to form into “needle-like” structures controlled by a hive mind. After constructing themselves into a needle, the mold begins by numbing a region of the wanderer’s body (typically the back), then piercing directly into their skin. The mold then embeds itself in the wanderer’s skin, spreading throughout their outer layers of skin. The mold utilizes advanced techniques to avoid detection, preventing an immune response.

Once the mold has embedded itself in the epidermis and dermis, it will begin pushing deeper, until it reaches the lowest regions of the hypodermis. After reaching such point, the mold will spread toward the muscles, taking complete control of the muscles. The mold will begin by individually plucking each hair out of its follicle, causing unimaginable pain and discomfort for the afflicted wanderer. The mold will then begin to manipulate the wanderer’s muscles, forcing them to stand still. The mold will then eat away at the hypodermis, dermis, and epidermis until the wanderer is left without any remaining skin. The mold will then retreat from its host, returning to its decrepit hiding place. The entire process can last for several weeks, possibly even months.

{{Blurimage|file=Schimmelplatz4.webp|align=center|caption=A photograph of an underground city on this level. Mold was accumulating on the lens.}}

===<span style="color:white;">Black Mold</span>===

Black Mold is a less common variant of mold found throughout The Schimmelplatz. Black Mold takes the appearance of a dark, grainy mold-like species. On the contrary to its counterparts, Black Mold is highly aggressive and is capable of physically attacking the wanderer. Unlike the colder, more calculating mold species, Black Mold appears to behave in a manner that could only be described as “Hot-Headed”. Black Mold has the most physical versatility out of any mold species, being capable of forming into life-sized creatures that act as a hive mind. These creatures may form from Black Mold at seemingly random intervals, engaging wanderers in a chase. Despite their deadly nature, they move at a relatively slow speed and have mobility issues, making them the least dangerous of the four species. 

===<span style="color:white;">Blood Mold</span>===

A highly toxic variant of the mold, Blood Mold takes the appearance of mold with a highly saturated scarlet tint. Blood Mold may also mix with other species of mold, primarily Black Mold. Blood Mold is, as of now, under continued experiment to verify its properties, origins, and remedies. 

Interestingly, Blood Mold does not appear to stalk, murder, or even attack the wanderer. The Mold takes a more cautious approach, instead choosing to infect the wanderer via entrance through the nostrils, mouth, or any other open region of the body. Once the Mold has settled within the body, it can lay dormant for decades, even passing on to the wanderer’s children if they are a biological female. The Mold does not appear to pass away from natural causes during this stage of infection, and likely cannot be removed without excruciating pain.

Once the Blood Mold decides to strike, it will begin a long trek toward the brain. Similar to the Lyssavirus (Rabies), the infection releases singular mold cells from the hive mind, dispatching them to hijack neurons. In the meantime, the hive mind will cause a distraction in order to prevent the immune system from responding with swift action toward the neuron-hijackers. This “distraction” usually consists of a three-pronged attack on the stomach, lungs, and intestines. This attack usually initiates symptoms of fever, fatigue, projectile vomit, diarrhea, and, in rare cases, internal bleeding.

Even if the immune system responds to the attack with decisive force, wiping out the entire hive mind, the Neuron-Hijackers will arrive at the brain.  Even singular cells are capable of overruling the entire brain, as they have the ability to completely hijack the brain as long as they are in contact with it. Once the hijackers reach the brain, it becomes far too late for treatment. The Blood Mold will order all cells to commit suicide, causing an explosion of flesh and bones within the infected. The mortality rate of the infection is estimated to be between 85-90%.

==<span style="color:white;">Entrances and Exits</span>==

===<span style="color:white;">Entrances</span>===

Due to the highly dangerous and unpredictable nature of The Schimmelplatz, most professionals do not recommend entering the level. Nevertheless, entrances must be made publicly available to prevent accidental entry.   

Nearly any level can transition into The Schimmelplatz, so long as the following criteria are met:
*The air quality in the transitioning region is poor.
*Small colonies of mold grow in said region.
*Said region is indoors, underground, or under a roof.
*Said region is located within The Backrooms.
*Said region does not contain a high volume of non-fungal entities.

===<span style="color:white;">Exits</span>===

*The luckiest of wanderers may come across a purple, neon door. Going through this door will return the wanderer to [[Level 0]].
*After traversing the vast landscape of the level, one may find themselves at a colossal steel door. The door may be activated with a button, revealing a portal within. All record of the portal’s contents have been lost, prompting new expeditions to be prepared for the near future.<div>


