===Log A (January 14th, 2003)===

The higher-ups said I needed to write in this thing, they said something about recording info or whatever bullshit. They didn’t tell us anything about this place beforehand, which obviously raised some eyebrows, but I don’t get paid in bulk provisions to sit around and look pretty (although I am pretty, not to brag). The only info we could squeeze out of them was something about mold and a horrible stench. I know I won’t be taking this hazmat suit off, that’s for sure.

=== Log B (January 16th, 2003)===

My god, this place is shaping up to be worse than hell. The stench is miserable, I can smell it through this suit. Worst part is that you never go noseblind to it, it’s still wafting through my nostrils two days later. One of our guys, Jared, decided to take his helmet off. He’s having trouble breathing, but it’s nothing a medic can’t fix. The mold is everywhere, even all over my visor. I have to stop every fifteen minutes just to wipe it off. Thank god we’re wearing these suits, or we’d be dead. Anyways, I’m running out of space on this page, guess I’ll write tomorrow.

===Log C (January 17th, 2003)===

Okay, the stench is really starting to mess with my brain. I can’t stand another second of this agony, and I’m sure the other members can’t either. It’s good to know that the higher-ups have assured us that this should be the point we find the exit, otherwise I don’t know what I’d do. The mold is intensifying, I have to wipe my visor off nearly every ten minutes at this point. As much as I hate to admit it, the other guys back at the main base might not be such pussies for refusing a mission like this. Jared isn’t doing too well, we have to carry him or he’ll get winded. Anyways, I’ll update tomorrow.

===Log D (January 19th, 2003)===

Skipped a few days, but I don’t care what the higher-ups have to say anymore. Jared told us to leave him behind, insisting that he just needed to catch his breath, and that he’d catch up in a bit. That was fourteen hours ago, and the growing wall of mold behind our group has stopped us from retrieving him. I hate to say it, but he’s almost certainly dead. One of our other group members, Lithia, accidentally broke her suit’s built-in feeding tube. If we don’t make it to the exit in time, I’m afraid she’ll have to choose between starvation and mold poisoning. Speaking of feeding tubes, the mold got uncomfortably close to bursting mine yesterday. I have a hunch that these things are smarter than we think, not just the usual stuff. They formed a “needle” and attempted to poke through when I was sleeping. I’m at a loss for words at how the smell is able to persist for so long. I don’t even know how to conclude this thing, so I’ll leave it at that.

===Log E (January 20th, 2003)===

The mold is showing more signs of sentience by the hour. I can feel those little microbastards, pushing and pulling on the fibers of my suit. Lithia’s entire suit was contaminated due to the feeding tube damage, so she’s now walking around without one. I can already see the mold growing on her hair, but I’m afraid she’ll panic if I tell her. It shouldn’t be too long until she finds out herself, anyways. We’re starting to have supply issues. Turns out the ten gallons of Almond Water wasn’t enough, fifteen would’ve been better. I’m starting to wonder if jumping into that deep pile of mold on the side of the road would be a quicker fate than slowly starving…

===Log F (January 21st, 2003)===

This is probably going to be my last log before I die or reach the exit, so I’m going to recount information about myself. My name is Marnette “May” Columbia, and I was born in The Frontrooms, Kansas, to be specific. I found my way here after- damn! I can’t even keep my story straight! Levels like this will do that to you. When Lithia died, I discovered why we were really sent here; to gather information, but not to return. They completely lied to us about the exit, lulling us into a false sense of security. Truth is, they had no damn clue when the exit would appear, or if there even is an exit, but it didn’t matter to them. Appropriately to the situation, they’ve cut off all signals from here to the main base. Only god can save our poor souls now.

===Log G (January 22nd, 2003)===

Surprisingly, I haven’t kicked the bucket yet. After Lithia’s death, we were left with only four group members. That number got cut down to three after one of our group members, Aleksander, fell head first into the mold. We don’t even know what happened to the poor guy, no screams or anything. I’d like to believe he died quickly, or maybe it noclipped him to a safer level, but you never know in a harrowing place like this. It’s down to just me, Caleb, Branden, and this rancid stench. My nostrils feel like a furnace. I’ve noticed blisters forming all over my nose, I don’t think that’s a normal occurrence. The mold has gotten so bad that I don’t even bother to wipe my visor off anymore. All of our hazmat suits have malfunctioned, and we will certainly be dead soon. 

===Log H (January 23rd, 2003)===

My god, I killed people. I had to do it, Caleb was hoarding the last gallon of Almond Water, and Branden’s skin was being eaten from the inside out. I killed them, both of them. Branden was a mercy kill, but I killed Caleb out of greed. I’m a murderer, I deserve to rot in the lowest layer of hell for what I did. I don’t know if I can- Holy shit! That’s a, that’s a door! I can escape from this hell! I can’t really describe how loud I’m yelling by writing on this piece of paper. Goodbye, stench, won’t miss you one bit!

=== Epilogue: Ten Years Later (May 6th, 2013)===
I can’t believe I found this thing again. I’ve been living on Level 10 for a little while, the solitude is long overdue. I still regret what I did back there, Caleb did not deserve to die. It was him or me, and I, selfishly, chose me. Every night, I can still hear his screams of pain. The image of me shoving his face into a pile of mold, watching those little beasts eat his face, while he was still alive. The stench has never gone away, I’ve just grown used to it. I’m going to throw this thing on the ground, and satisfyingly watch it blow away in the wind. Burning it would be an easier solution, but I don’t want any other wanderer make the same mistake I did. To whoever this reaches, if anybody, I hope it finds you well.

'''-Marnette “May” Columbia'''</div> 
